      "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>This post is adapted from a Zhihu article (Chinese): <a href=\"https://www.zhihu.com/tardis/zm/art/187305388\">没想到一书《程序员的自我修养》对我启发如此大？？？</a>, by @一包伤心的辣条. It summarizes <em>The Self-Cultivation of Programmers</em> by Chen Yihe. Rights belong to the original author and publisher.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>The full article is available in Chinese at <code>/zh/blog/programmer-self-cultivation</code>. Below is a brief English overview of the main themes.</p>\n<h2>Career</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Know yourself; outwork average effort when other advice fails.</li>\n<li>Build authority through real skill, then show it at the right time.</li>\n<li>Follow best practices; stay curious; communicate beyond code.</li>\n<li>Work with strong people; treat life, sleep, and travel as part of growth.</li>\n<li>Pay is tied to how hard you are to replace, not raw workload.</li>\n<li>Deep involvement in one project beats shallow touches on many.</li>\n<li>Keep learning; protect your reputation with rigor.</li>\n<li>Don't say \"easy\" or \"impossible\" without analysis; collaborate instead of solo heroics.</li>\n<li>Learn self-marketing: read outside tech, write clear docs.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Practice and thinking</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>See the problem behind the technology (e.g. missing user feedback vs. \"system broken\").</li>\n<li>Speak up like an expert when you truly understand; learn broadly for perspective.</li>\n<li>Regain creativity through daily reading, weekly blogging, and capturing fleeting ideas.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Personal development</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>Never stop learning; admit mistakes quickly.</li>\n<li>Experts differ in <strong>awareness</strong>—not just experience.</li>\n<li>Prefer \"wet\" learning (reflection, talks, writing) over hoarding \"dry\" listicles you never apply.</li>\n</ul>\n"
